      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying for a food chem test and i keep getting confused about the browning process. can u explain what the maillard reaction actually is and what temps i need to look out for to make sure it happens during baking?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a fascinating chemical process, like a very complex, high-temperature browning that happens when amino acids and reducing sugars react. It's what gives roasted coffee, seared steaks, and perfectly browned bread that wonderful, complex flavor and color. You can really see it happening when you're baking, and it generally kicks off when the temperature gets high enough to start the chemical dance, usually above about 285°F (140°C). If your oven is too cool, your bread will just be pale and doughy, not golden brown like a successful batch of baked goods!",
